3
00:00:12,620 --> 00:00:20,620
Reading by Annie Coleman in St. Louis, Missouri, on January 9, 2006.

4
00:00:20,620 --> 00:00:24,620
Pride and Prejudice by Jane Austen.

5
00:00:24,620 --> 00:00:27,620
Chapter 47

6
00:00:27,620 --> 00:00:33,620
I have been thinking it over again, Elizabeth," said her uncle as they drove from the town.

7
00:00:33,620 --> 00:00:41,620
And really, upon serious consideration, I am much more inclined than I was to judge as your elder sister does on the matter.

8
00:00:41,620 --> 00:00:50,620
It appears to me so very unlikely that any young man should form such a design against a girl who is by no means unprotected or friendless,

9
00:00:50,620 --> 00:00:57,620
and who is actually staying in his Colonel's family, that I am strongly inclined to hope the best.

10
00:00:57,620 --> 00:01:07,620
Could he expect that her friends would not step forward? Could he expect to be noticed again by the regiment after such an affront to Colonel Forster?

11
00:01:07,620 --> 00:01:10,620
His temptation is not adequate to the risk.

12
00:01:10,620 --> 00:01:15,620
Do you really think so? cried Elizabeth, brightening up for a moment.

13
00:01:15,620 --> 00:01:21,620
Upon my word, said Mrs. Gardiner, I begin to be of your uncle's opinion.

14
00:01:21,620 --> 00:01:27,620
It is really too great a violation of decency, honor, and interest for him to be guilty of.

15
00:01:27,620 --> 00:01:30,620
I cannot think so very ill of Wickham.

16
00:01:30,620 --> 00:01:36,620
Can you yourself, Lizzie, so wholly give him up as to believe him capable of it?

17
00:01:36,620 --> 00:01:43,620
Not perhaps of neglecting his own interest, but of every other neglect I can believe him capable.

18
00:01:43,620 --> 00:01:45,620
If indeed it should be so.

19
00:01:45,620 --> 00:01:51,620
But I dare not hope it. Why should they not go on to Scotland if that had been the case?

20
00:01:51,620 --> 00:01:58,620
In the first place, replied Mr. Gardiner, there is no absolute proof that they are not gone to Scotland.

21
00:01:58,620 --> 00:02:08,620
Oh, but they're removing from the shays into a hackney-coach is such a presumption, and besides no traces of them were to be found on the Barnett Road.

22
00:02:09,620 --> 00:02:17,620
While then supposing them to be in London, they may be there, though for the purpose of concealment, for no more exceptional purpose.

23
00:02:17,620 --> 00:02:30,620
It is not likely that money should be very abundant on either side, and it might strike them that they could be more economically, though lex expeditiously, married in London than in Scotland.

24
00:02:30,620 --> 00:02:37,620
But why all this secrecy? Why any fear of detection? Why must their marriage be private?

25
00:02:37,620 --> 00:02:47,620
Oh, no, no, this is not likely. His most particular friend, you see, by Jane's account, was persuaded of his never-intending to marry her.

26
00:02:47,620 --> 00:03:04,620
Wickham will never marry a woman without some money. He cannot afford it. And what claims has Lydia? What attraction has she beyond youth, health, and good humour that can make him, for her sake, forgo every chance of benefiting himself by marrying well?

27
00:03:04,620 --> 00:03:16,620
As to what restraints the apprehensions of disgrace in the core might throw on a dishonourable elopement with her, I am not able to judge, for I know nothing of the effects that such a step might produce.

28
00:03:16,620 --> 00:03:33,620
But as to your other objection, I am afraid it will hardly hold good. Lydia has no brothers to step forward, and he might imagine, from my father's behaviour, from his indolence and the little attention he has ever seemed to give to what was going forward in his family,

29
00:03:33,620 --> 00:03:40,620
that he would do as little, and think as little about it, as any father could do in such a matter.

30
00:03:40,620 --> 00:03:48,620
But can you think that Lydia is so lost to everything but love of him as to consent to live with him on any terms other than marriage?

31
00:03:49,620 --> 00:04:03,620
It does seem, and it is most shocking indeed, replied Elizabeth with tears in her eyes, that a sister's sense of decency and virtue in such a point should admit of doubt. But really I know not what to say.

32
00:04:03,620 --> 00:04:18,620
Perhaps I am not doing her justice, but she is very young. She has never been taught to think on serious subjects, and for the last half year, nay, for a twelve-month, she has been given up to nothing but amusement and vanity.

33
00:04:18,620 --> 00:04:25,620
She has been allowed to dispose of her time in the most idle and frivolous manner and to adopt any opinions that came in her way.

34
00:04:25,620 --> 00:04:51,620
Since the blank sheer were first quartered in Maryton, nothing but love, flirtation, and officers have been in her head. She has been doing everything in her power by thinking and talking on the subject to give greater, hmm, what shall I call it, susceptibility to her feelings, which are naturally lively enough, and we all know that Wickham has every charm of person and address that can captivate a woman.

35
00:04:51,620 --> 00:04:59,620
But you see that Jane, said her aunt, does not think so very ill of Wickham as to believe him capable of the attempt.

36
00:05:00,170 --> 00:05:03,170
Of whom does Jane ever think ill?

37
00:05:03,170 --> 00:05:08,250
And who is there, whatever might be their former conduct, that she would think capable of such

38
00:05:08,250 --> 00:05:11,610
an attempt till it were proved against them?

39
00:05:11,610 --> 00:05:16,010
But Jane knows, as well as I do, what Wickham really is.

40
00:05:16,010 --> 00:05:20,650
We both know that he has been profligate in every sense of the word, that he has neither

41
00:05:20,650 --> 00:05:26,330
integrity nor honour, that he is as false and deceitful as he is insinuating.

42
00:05:27,210 --> 00:05:32,730
And do you really know all this? cried Mrs. Gardiner, whose curiosity as to the

43
00:05:32,730 --> 00:05:35,210
mode of her intelligence was all alive.

44
00:05:36,170 --> 00:05:39,130
I do indeed, replied Elizabeth, colouring.

45
00:05:40,010 --> 00:05:45,290
I told you the other day of his infamous behaviour to Mr. Darcy, and you yourself,

46
00:05:45,290 --> 00:05:49,290
when last at Longbourn, heard in what manner he spoke of the man who had

47
00:05:49,290 --> 00:05:52,490
behaved with such forbearance and liberality towards him.

48
00:05:53,290 --> 00:05:57,450
And there are other circumstances which I am not at liberty, which it is not

49
00:05:57,450 --> 00:05:58,810
worthwhile to relate.

50
00:05:59,450 --> 00:06:02,810
But his lies about the whole Pemberley family are endless.

51
00:06:03,370 --> 00:06:07,530
From what he said of Miss Darcy, I was thoroughly prepared to see a proud,

52
00:06:07,530 --> 00:06:09,290
reserved, disagreeable girl.

53
00:06:09,930 --> 00:06:12,170
Yet he knew to the contrary himself.

54
00:06:12,810 --> 00:06:16,890
He must know that she was as amiable and unpretending as we have found her.

55
00:06:18,170 --> 00:06:20,330
But does Lydia know nothing of this?

56
00:06:20,410 --> 00:06:24,090
Can she be ignorant of what you and Jane seem so well to understand?

57
00:06:25,450 --> 00:06:28,330
Oh yes, that, that is the worst of all.

58
00:06:28,890 --> 00:06:33,770
Till I was in Kent and saw so much both of Mr. Darcy and his relation,

59
00:06:33,770 --> 00:06:39,530
Colonel Fitzwilliam, I was ignorant of the truth myself, and when I returned home

60
00:06:39,530 --> 00:06:43,290
the blank sheer was to leave Maritain in a week or fort's night time.

61
00:06:44,090 --> 00:06:48,890
As that was the case, neither Jane to whom I related the whole, nor I

62
00:06:48,890 --> 00:06:52,570
thought it necessary to make our knowledge public, for of what use

63
00:06:52,570 --> 00:06:56,570
could it apparently be to any one, that the good opinion which all the

64
00:06:56,570 --> 00:06:59,530
neighborhood had of him should then be overthrown.

65
00:07:00,250 --> 00:07:04,010
And even when it was settled that Lydia should go with Mrs. Forster,

66
00:07:04,010 --> 00:07:07,450
the necessity of opening her eyes to his character never occurred to

67
00:07:07,450 --> 00:07:11,450
me, that she could be in any danger from the deception never

68
00:07:11,450 --> 00:07:16,090
entered my head, that such a consequence as this could ensue,

69
00:07:16,090 --> 00:07:19,210
you may easily believe, was far enough from my thoughts.

70
00:07:20,650 --> 00:07:23,370
When they are all removed to Brighton, therefore you had no reason,

71
00:07:23,370 --> 00:07:25,450
I suppose, to believe them fond of each other.

72
00:07:26,570 --> 00:07:30,570
Not the slightest. I can remember no symptom of affection on either

73
00:07:30,570 --> 00:07:34,570
side, and had anything of the kind been perceptible, you must

74
00:07:34,570 --> 00:07:38,010
be aware that ours is not a family on which it could be thrown away.

75
00:07:38,730 --> 00:07:41,930
When he first entered the core, she was ready enough to

76
00:07:41,930 --> 00:07:47,290
admire him, but so we all were. Every girl in or near Mariton was out

77
00:07:47,290 --> 00:07:50,650
of her senses about him for the first two months, but he never

78
00:07:50,650 --> 00:07:55,130
distinguished her by any particular attention, and consequently

79
00:07:55,130 --> 00:07:59,450
after a moderate period of extravagant and wild admiration her

80
00:07:59,450 --> 00:08:03,210
fancy for him gave way, and others of the regiment who treated

81
00:08:03,210 --> 00:08:06,490
her with more distinction again became her favorites.

82
00:08:06,890 --> 00:08:10,970
It may be easily believed that however little of novelty could be

83
00:08:10,970 --> 00:08:14,170
added to their fears, hopes, and conjectures on this

84
00:08:14,170 --> 00:08:18,650
interesting subject by its repeated discussion, no other could

85
00:08:18,650 --> 00:08:21,850
detain them from it long during the whole of the journey.

86
00:08:22,810 --> 00:08:27,450
From Elizabeth's thoughts it was never absent. Fixed there by

87
00:08:27,450 --> 00:08:31,690
the keenest of all anguish, self-approach, she could find no

88
00:08:31,690 --> 00:08:34,170
interval of ease or forgetfulness.

89
00:08:34,170 --> 00:08:38,170
They traveled as expeditiously as possible, and sleeping one night

90
00:08:38,170 --> 00:08:41,770
on the road, reached long-born by dinnertime the next day.

91
00:08:42,490 --> 00:08:45,850
It was a comfort to Elizabeth to consider that Jane could not

92
00:08:45,850 --> 00:08:48,250
have been wearied by long expectations.

93
00:08:49,290 --> 00:08:53,050
The little gardeners attracted by the sight of a sheaes were

94
00:08:53,050 --> 00:08:55,370
standing on the steps of the house as they entered the

95
00:08:55,370 --> 00:08:59,050
paddock, and when the carriage drove up to the door, the

96
00:08:59,050 --> 00:09:03,210
joyful surprise that lighted up their faces, the little

97
00:09:03,210 --> 00:09:06,650
gardeners gathered up their faces, and displayed itself over

98
00:09:06,650 --> 00:09:11,450
their whole bodies in a variety of capers and frisks, was the

99
00:09:11,450 --> 00:09:13,610
first pleasing earnest of their welcome.

100
00:09:14,650 --> 00:09:17,930
Elizabeth jumped out, and after giving each of them a hasty

101
00:09:17,930 --> 00:09:22,090
kiss, hurried into the vestibule, where Jane, who came running

102
00:09:22,090 --> 00:09:25,450
down from her mother's apartment, immediately met her.

103
00:09:26,330 --> 00:09:30,250
Elizabeth, as she affectionately embraced her, whilst tears

104
00:09:30,250 --> 00:09:34,250
both, lost not a moment in asking whether anything had been heard

105
00:09:34,250 --> 00:09:35,210
of the fugitives.

106
00:09:36,330 --> 00:09:40,330
Not yet, replied Jane, but now that my dear uncle is come I hope

107
00:09:40,330 --> 00:09:41,450
everything will be well.

108
00:09:42,490 --> 00:09:43,690
Is my father in town?

109
00:09:44,490 --> 00:09:46,890
Yes, he went on Tuesday, as I wrote you word.

110
00:09:47,530 --> 00:09:48,890
And have you heard from him often?

111
00:09:49,850 --> 00:09:51,610
We have heard only twice.

112
00:09:51,610 --> 00:09:54,170
He wrote me a few lines on Wednesday to say that he had

113
00:09:54,170 --> 00:09:57,610
arrived in safety, and to give me his directions, which I

114
00:09:57,610 --> 00:09:59,210
particularly begged him to do.

115
00:09:59,740 --> 00:10:04,860
He merely added that he should not write again till he had something of importance to mention.

116
00:10:04,860 --> 00:10:07,260
And my mother, how is she?

117
00:10:07,260 --> 00:10:09,300
How are you all?

118
00:10:09,300 --> 00:10:13,860
My mother is tolerably well, I trust, though her spirits are greatly shaken.

119
00:10:13,860 --> 00:10:18,100
She is upstairs, and will have great satisfaction in seeing you all.

120
00:10:18,100 --> 00:10:20,740
She does not yet leave her dressing-room.

121
00:10:20,740 --> 00:10:23,660
Mary and Kitty, thank heaven, are quite well.

122
00:10:24,660 --> 00:10:27,700
But you, how are you? cried Elizabeth.

123
00:10:27,700 --> 00:10:29,020
You look pale.

124
00:10:29,020 --> 00:10:31,540
How much you must have gone through!

125
00:10:31,540 --> 00:10:36,620
Her sister, however, assured her of being perfectly well, and their conversation, which had been

126
00:10:36,620 --> 00:10:42,460
passing while Mr. and Mrs. Gardiner were engaged with their children, was now put an end to

127
00:10:42,460 --> 00:10:45,420
by the approach of the whole party.

128
00:10:45,420 --> 00:10:50,660
Jane ran to her uncle and aunt and welcomed and thanked them both, with alternate smiles

129
00:10:50,660 --> 00:10:52,700
and tears.

130
00:10:52,700 --> 00:10:56,660
When they were all in the drawing-room, the questions which Elizabeth had already asked

131
00:10:56,660 --> 00:11:01,140
were of course repeated by the others, and they soon found that Jane had no intelligence

132
00:11:01,140 --> 00:11:02,700
to give.

133
00:11:02,700 --> 00:11:07,220
The sanguine hope of good, however, which the benevolence of her heart suggested, had

134
00:11:07,220 --> 00:11:09,140
not yet deserted her.

135
00:11:09,140 --> 00:11:13,420
She still expected that it would all end well, and that every morning would bring some

136
00:11:13,420 --> 00:11:19,540
letter, either from Lydia or her father, to explain their proceedings, and perhaps

137
00:11:19,540 --> 00:11:22,180
announce their marriage.

138
00:11:22,180 --> 00:11:26,860
Mrs. Bennet, to whose apartment they all repaired, after a few minutes' conversation

139
00:11:26,860 --> 00:11:31,220
together, received them exactly as might be expected.

140
00:11:31,220 --> 00:11:36,540
With tears and lamentations of regret, invectives against the villainous conduct

141
00:11:36,540 --> 00:11:41,620
of Wickham, and complaints of her own sufferings and ill usage, blaming

142
00:11:41,620 --> 00:11:46,220
everybody but the person to whose ill-judging indulgence the errors of

143
00:11:46,220 --> 00:11:48,740
her daughter must principally be owing.

144
00:11:49,660 --> 00:11:54,020
If I had been able, said she, to carry my point, and going to brighten with

145
00:11:54,020 --> 00:11:58,460
all my family, this would not have happened, but poor dear Lydia had

146
00:11:58,460 --> 00:12:00,860
nobody to take care of her.

147
00:12:00,860 --> 00:12:03,780
Why did the Forsters ever let her go out of their sight?

148
00:12:03,780 --> 00:12:07,300
I am sure there was some great neglector other on their side, for she

149
00:12:07,300 --> 00:12:10,180
is not the kind of girl to do such a thing if she had been well

150
00:12:10,180 --> 00:12:11,660
looked after.

151
00:12:11,660 --> 00:12:15,180
I always thought they were very unfit to have the charge of her, but

152
00:12:15,180 --> 00:12:18,540
I was overruled, as I always am.

153
00:12:18,540 --> 00:12:20,300
Poor dear child!

154
00:12:20,300 --> 00:12:24,980
And now here's Mr. Bennet gone away, and I know he will fight Wickham,

155
00:12:24,980 --> 00:12:27,460
wherever he meets him, and then he will be killed, and what is to

156
00:12:27,460 --> 00:12:29,100
become of us all?

157
00:12:29,100 --> 00:12:32,260
The Collinses will turn us out before he is cold in his grave, and if

158
00:12:32,260 --> 00:12:37,100
you are not kind to us, brother, I do not know what we shall do.

159
00:12:37,100 --> 00:12:42,100
They all exclaimed against such terrific ideas, and Mr. Gardiner,

160
00:12:42,100 --> 00:12:45,740
after general assurances of his affection for her and all her

161
00:12:45,740 --> 00:12:49,820
family, told her that he meant to be in London the very next day,

162
00:12:49,820 --> 00:12:54,900
and would assist Mr. Bennet in every endeavour for recovering Lydia.

163
00:12:54,900 --> 00:12:59,260
Do not give way to useless alarm, added he, though it is right to be

164
00:12:59,260 --> 00:13:02,900
prepared for the worst, there is no occasion to look on it as

165
00:13:02,900 --> 00:13:03,900
certain.

166
00:13:03,900 --> 00:13:07,620
It is not quite a week since they left Brighton, and a few days

167
00:13:07,620 --> 00:13:11,340
more we may gain some news of them, and till we know that they

168
00:13:11,340 --> 00:13:15,260
are not married, and have no design of marrying, do not let

169
00:13:15,260 --> 00:13:17,940
us give the matter over as lost.

170
00:13:17,940 --> 00:13:21,260
As soon as I get to town I shall go to my brother, and make him come

171
00:13:21,260 --> 00:13:24,420
home with me to Grace Church Street, and then we may consult

172
00:13:24,420 --> 00:13:26,940
together as to what is to be done.

173
00:13:26,940 --> 00:13:31,940
Oh, my dear brother, replied Mrs. Bennet, that is exactly what I

174
00:13:31,940 --> 00:13:36,380
could most wish for, and now do, when you get to town, find

175
00:13:36,380 --> 00:13:39,380
them out wherever they may be, and if they are not married

176
00:13:39,380 --> 00:13:43,100
already, make them marry, and as for wedding clothes, do not

177
00:13:43,100 --> 00:13:45,620
let them wait for that, but tell Lydia she shall have as much

178
00:13:45,620 --> 00:13:49,460
money as she chooses to buy them, after they are married, and above

179
00:13:49,460 --> 00:13:52,340
all keep Mr. Bennet from fighting.

180
00:13:52,340 --> 00:13:55,540
Tell him what a dreadful state I am in, that I am frighted out

181
00:13:55,540 --> 00:13:59,420
of my wits, and have such trumblings, such flutterings all over

182
00:13:59,420 --> 00:14:03,340
me, such spasms in my side, and pains in my head, and such

183
00:14:03,340 --> 00:14:07,820
beatings at heart, that I can get no rest by night nor by day.

184
00:14:07,820 --> 00:14:10,540
And tell my dear Lydia not to give any directions about her

185
00:14:10,540 --> 00:14:13,580
clothes till she has seen me, for she does not know which are the

186
00:14:13,580 --> 00:14:15,060
best warehouses.

187
00:14:15,060 --> 00:14:17,420
Oh, brother, how kind you are!

188
00:14:17,420 --> 00:14:20,540
I know you will contrive it all.

189
00:14:20,540 --> 00:14:23,500
But Mr. Gardiner, though he assured her again of his earnest

190
00:14:23,500 --> 00:14:27,220
endeavours in the cause, could not avoid recommending moderation

191
00:14:27,220 --> 00:14:31,740
to her, as well in her hopes as her fear, and after talking

192
00:14:31,740 --> 00:14:34,580
with her in this manner till dinner was on the table, they

193
00:14:34,580 --> 00:14:37,860
all left her to vent all her feelings on the housekeeper,

194
00:14:37,860 --> 00:14:41,340
who attended in the absence of her daughters.

195
00:14:41,340 --> 00:14:44,460
Though her brother and sister were persuaded that there was no

196
00:14:44,460 --> 00:14:48,420
relocation for such a seclusion from the family, they did not

197
00:14:48,420 --> 00:14:51,740
attempt to oppose it, for they knew that she had not prudence

198
00:14:51,740 --> 00:14:54,660
enough to hold her tongue before the servants while they waited

199
00:14:54,660 --> 00:14:58,620
at table, and judged it better that one only of the household

200
00:14:58,820 --> 00:15:03,980
and the one whom they could most trust should comprehend all her fears and solicitude on

201
00:15:03,980 --> 00:15:06,500
the subject.

202
00:15:06,500 --> 00:15:12,180
In the dining-room they were soon joined by Mary and Kitty, who had been too busily engaged

203
00:15:12,180 --> 00:15:16,500
in their separate apartments to make their appearance before.

204
00:15:16,500 --> 00:15:20,540
One came from her books, and the other from her toilette.

205
00:15:20,540 --> 00:15:26,780
The faces of both, however, were tolerably calm, and no change was visible in either,

206
00:15:26,940 --> 00:15:31,660
that the loss of her favourite sister, or the anger which she had herself incurred in

207
00:15:31,660 --> 00:15:38,660
this business, had given more of fretfulness than usual to the accents of Kitty.

208
00:15:38,660 --> 00:15:43,980
As for Mary, she was mistress enough of herself to whisper to Elizabeth, with accountants

209
00:15:43,980 --> 00:15:48,900
of grave reflection soon after they were seated at the table.

210
00:15:48,900 --> 00:15:54,500
This is a most unfortunate affair, and will probably be much talked of, but we must

211
00:15:54,500 --> 00:16:01,220
stem the tide of malice and pour into the wounded bosoms of each other the balm of sisterly

212
00:16:01,220 --> 00:16:03,740
consolation.

213
00:16:03,740 --> 00:16:08,620
Then, perceiving in Elizabeth no inclination of replying, she added,

214
00:16:08,620 --> 00:16:15,700
Unhappy as the event must be for Lydia, we may draw from it this useful lesson, that

215
00:16:15,700 --> 00:16:21,620
loss of virtue in a female is irretrievable, that one false step involves her in

216
00:16:21,620 --> 00:16:27,580
endless ruin, that her reputation is no less brittle than it is beautiful,

217
00:16:27,580 --> 00:16:31,980
and that she cannot be too much guarded in her behaviour towards the undeserving

218
00:16:31,980 --> 00:16:34,980
of the other sex.

219
00:16:34,980 --> 00:16:38,660
Elizabeth lifted up her eyes in amazement, but was too much oppressed

220
00:16:38,660 --> 00:16:41,060
to make any reply.

221
00:16:41,060 --> 00:16:45,420
Mary, however, continued to console herself with such kind of moral

222
00:16:45,420 --> 00:16:49,100
extractions from the evil before them.

223
00:16:49,100 --> 00:16:53,280
In the afternoon the two elder Miss Bennets were able to be for half an hour

224
00:16:53,280 --> 00:16:58,300
by themselves, and Elizabeth instantly availed herself of the opportunity

225
00:16:58,300 --> 00:17:04,260
of making any inquiries which Jane was equally eager to satisfy.

226
00:17:04,260 --> 00:17:09,260
After joining in general lamentations over the dreadful sequel of this event,

227
00:17:09,260 --> 00:17:13,220
which Elizabeth considered as all but certain, and Miss Bennet could not

228
00:17:13,220 --> 00:17:17,780
assert to be wholly impossible, the former continued the subject by

229
00:17:17,780 --> 00:17:21,700
saying, But tell me all and everything about it which I have not

230
00:17:21,700 --> 00:17:23,260
already heard.

231
00:17:23,260 --> 00:17:25,260
Give me further particulars.

232
00:17:25,260 --> 00:17:27,220
What did Colonel Forster say?

233
00:17:27,220 --> 00:17:31,180
Had they no apprehension of anything before the elopement took place?

234
00:17:31,180 --> 00:17:34,780
They must have seen them together for ever.

235
00:17:34,780 --> 00:17:39,460
Colonel Forster did own that he had often suspected some partiality,

236
00:17:39,460 --> 00:17:43,300
especially on Lydia's side, but nothing to give him any alarm.

237
00:17:43,300 --> 00:17:45,740
I am so grieved for him.

238
00:17:45,740 --> 00:17:49,340
His behaviour was attentive and kind to the utmost.

239
00:17:49,340 --> 00:17:54,260
He was coming to us in order to assure us of his concern before he had

240
00:17:54,260 --> 00:17:57,740
any idea of there not being gone to Scotland.

241
00:17:57,740 --> 00:18:02,780
When that apprehension first got abroad it hastened his journey.

242
00:18:02,780 --> 00:18:05,540
And was Denny convinced that Wickham would not marry?

243
00:18:05,540 --> 00:18:08,020
Did he know of their intending to go off?

244
00:18:08,020 --> 00:18:10,780
Had Colonel Forster seen Denny himself?

245
00:18:10,780 --> 00:18:15,220
Yes, but when questioned by him, Denny denied knowing anything

246
00:18:15,220 --> 00:18:19,220
of their plans, and would not give his real opinion about it.

247
00:18:19,220 --> 00:18:22,500
He did not repeat his persuasion of their not marrying, and from

248
00:18:22,500 --> 00:18:28,100
that I am inclined to hope he might have been misunderstood before.

249
00:18:28,100 --> 00:18:31,660
Until Colonel Forster came himself, not one of you entertained a doubt,

250
00:18:31,660 --> 00:18:35,100
I suppose, of their being really married.

251
00:18:35,100 --> 00:18:38,620
How was it possible that such an idea could enter our brains?

252
00:18:38,620 --> 00:18:42,320
I felt a little uneasy, a little fearful of my sister's happiness

253
00:18:42,320 --> 00:18:45,800
with him in marriage, because I knew that his conduct had not been

254
00:18:45,800 --> 00:18:47,720
always quite right.

255
00:18:47,720 --> 00:18:49,840
My father and mother knew nothing of that.

256
00:18:49,840 --> 00:18:53,880
They only felt how imprudent a match it must be.

257
00:18:53,880 --> 00:18:57,680
Kitty then owned, with a very natural triumph, unknowing more than the

258
00:18:57,680 --> 00:19:03,120
rest of us, that in Lydia's last pletter she had prepared her for such a step.

259
00:19:03,120 --> 00:19:07,720
She had known, it seems, of their being in love with each other many weeks.

260
00:19:07,720 --> 00:19:09,680
But not before they went to Brighton?

261
00:19:09,680 --> 00:19:12,240
No, I believe not.

262
00:19:12,240 --> 00:19:15,960
Did Colonel Forster appear to think well of Wickham himself?

263
00:19:15,960 --> 00:19:18,400
Does he know his real character?

264
00:19:18,400 --> 00:19:23,280
I must confess that he did not speak so well of Wickham as he formerly did.

265
00:19:23,280 --> 00:19:27,440
He believed him to be imprudent and extravagant, and since this sad

266
00:19:27,440 --> 00:19:32,840
affair has taken place, it is said that he left Mariton greatly in debt.

267
00:19:32,840 --> 00:19:35,320
But I hope this may be false.

268
00:19:35,320 --> 00:19:40,440
Oh Jane, had we been less secret, had we told what we knew of him,

269
00:19:40,440 --> 00:19:43,360
this could not have happened.

270
00:19:43,360 --> 00:19:46,400
Perhaps it would have been better, replied her sister.

271
00:19:46,400 --> 00:19:50,320
But to expose the former faults of any person, without knowing what

272
00:19:50,320 --> 00:19:54,280
their present feelings were, seemed unjustifiable.

273
00:19:54,280 --> 00:19:56,240
We acted with the best intentions.

274
00:19:56,880 --> 00:20:01,800
Could Colonel Forster repeat the particulars of Lydia's note to his wife?

275
00:20:01,800 --> 00:20:04,880
He brought it with him for us to see.

276
00:20:04,880 --> 00:20:09,360
Jane then took it from her pocket-book, and gave it to Elizabeth.

277
00:20:09,360 --> 00:20:11,160
These were the contents.

278
00:20:11,160 --> 00:20:16,840
"'My dear Harriet, you will laugh when you know where I am gone, and I cannot help laughing

279
00:20:16,840 --> 00:20:21,160
myself at your surprise tomorrow morning, as soon as I am missed.

280
00:20:21,160 --> 00:20:26,840
I am going to Gretna Green, and if you cannot guess with who, I shall think you a simpleton,

281
00:20:26,920 --> 00:20:31,360
for there is but one man in the world I love, and he is an angel.

282
00:20:31,360 --> 00:20:35,880
I should never be happy without him, so think it no harm to be off.

283
00:20:35,880 --> 00:20:40,000
You need not send them word at long-born of my going, if you do not like it, for it will

284
00:20:40,000 --> 00:20:45,080
make the surprise the greater when I write to them and sign my name, Lydia Wickham.

285
00:20:45,080 --> 00:20:46,960
What a good joke it will be!

286
00:20:46,960 --> 00:20:49,160
I can hardly write for laughing.

287
00:20:49,160 --> 00:20:54,880
Pray make my excuses to Pratt for not keeping my engagement and dancing with him to-night.

288
00:20:54,920 --> 00:20:58,920
Tell him I hope he will excuse me when he knows all, and tell him I will dance with him

289
00:20:58,920 --> 00:21:02,080
at the next ball we meet, with great pleasure.

290
00:21:02,080 --> 00:21:06,240
I shall send for my clothes when I get to Longbourn, but I wish you would tell Sally

291
00:21:06,240 --> 00:21:10,800
to mend a great slit in my worked muslin gown before they are packed up.

292
00:21:10,800 --> 00:21:13,480
Goodbye, give my love to Colonel Forster.

293
00:21:13,480 --> 00:21:16,120
I hope you will drink to our good journey.

294
00:21:16,120 --> 00:21:18,480
Your affectionate friend, Lydia Bennet."

295
00:21:19,480 --> 00:21:26,080
Oh, thoughtless, thoughtless Lydia! cried Elizabeth when she had finished it.

296
00:21:26,080 --> 00:21:29,600
What a letter is this to be written at such a moment!

297
00:21:29,600 --> 00:21:34,160
But at least it shows that she was serious on the subject of their journey.

298
00:21:34,160 --> 00:21:38,960
Whatever he might afterwards have persuaded her to, it was not on her side a scheme of

299
00:21:38,960 --> 00:21:40,480
infamy.

300
00:21:40,480 --> 00:21:45,000
My poor father, how he must have felt it!

301
00:21:45,000 --> 00:21:47,320
I never saw anyone so shocked.

302
00:21:47,360 --> 00:21:50,520
He could not speak a word for full ten minutes.

303
00:21:50,520 --> 00:21:55,440
My mother was taken ill immediately, and the whole house in such confusion.

304
00:21:55,440 --> 00:22:01,480
Oh, Jane! cried Elizabeth, was there a servant belonging to it who did not know the whole

305
00:22:01,480 --> 00:22:04,560
story before the end of the day?

306
00:22:04,560 --> 00:22:10,720
I do not know, I hope there was, but to be guarded at such a time is very difficult.

307
00:22:10,720 --> 00:22:14,840
My mother was in hysterics, and though I endeavored to give her every assistance

308
00:22:14,880 --> 00:22:20,400
in my power, I am afraid I did not do so much as I might have done.

309
00:22:20,400 --> 00:22:25,960
But the horror of what might possibly happen almost took me from my faculties.

310
00:22:25,960 --> 00:22:28,900
Your attendance upon her has been too much for you.

311
00:22:28,900 --> 00:22:30,400
You do not look well.

312
00:22:30,400 --> 00:22:32,880
Oh, that I had been with you!

313
00:22:32,880 --> 00:22:37,720
You have had every care and anxiety upon yourself alone.

314
00:22:37,720 --> 00:22:42,520
Mary and Kitty have been very kind, and would have shared in every fatigue, I am sure.

315
00:22:43,040 --> 00:22:46,080
But I did not think it right for either of them.

316
00:22:46,080 --> 00:22:51,760
Kitty is slight and delicate, and Mary studies so much that her hours of repose should not

317
00:22:51,760 --> 00:22:53,640
be broken in on.

318
00:22:53,640 --> 00:22:58,400
My aunt Phillips came to Longbourn on Tuesday after my father went away, and was so good

319
00:22:58,400 --> 00:23:01,000
as to stay till Thursday with me.

320
00:23:01,000 --> 00:23:06,320
She was of great use and comfort to us all, and Lady Lucas has been very kind.

321
00:23:06,320 --> 00:23:10,880
She walked here on Wednesday morning to condole with us, and offered her services,

322
00:23:10,880 --> 00:23:14,960
or any of her daughters, if they should be of use to us.

323
00:23:14,960 --> 00:23:18,440
She had better have stayed at home, cried Elizabeth.

324
00:23:18,440 --> 00:23:24,600
Perhaps she meant well, but under such a misfortune as this one cannot see too little of one's

325
00:23:24,600 --> 00:23:26,120
neighbours.

326
00:23:26,120 --> 00:23:29,680
Assistance is impossible, condolence insufferable.

327
00:23:29,680 --> 00:23:34,000
Let them triumph over us at a distance, and be satisfied.

328
00:23:34,000 --> 00:23:39,160
She then proceeded to inquire into the measures which her father had intended to pursue,

329
00:23:39,160 --> 00:23:42,240
well in town, for the recovery of his daughter.

330
00:23:42,240 --> 00:23:49,320
He meant, I believe, replied Jane, to go to Epsom, a place where they last changed horses,

331
00:23:49,320 --> 00:23:54,160
see the postillions, and try if anything could be made out from them.

332
00:23:54,160 --> 00:23:58,520
His principal object must be to discover the number of the Hackney coach which took

333
00:23:58,520 --> 00:24:00,280
them from Clapham.

334
00:24:00,280 --> 00:24:04,760
It had come with a fare from London, and has he thought that the circumstance of a gentleman

335
00:24:04,760 --> 00:24:09,800
and a lady's removing from one carriage into another might be remarked, he meant to

336
00:24:09,800 --> 00:24:12,000
make inquiries at Clapham.

337
00:24:12,000 --> 00:24:16,880
If he could anyhow discover at what house the coachman had before set down his fare,

338
00:24:16,880 --> 00:24:21,120
he determined to make inquiries there, and hoped it might not be impossible to find

339
00:24:21,120 --> 00:24:24,000
out the stand and number of the coach.

340
00:24:24,000 --> 00:24:28,640
I do not know of any other designs that he had formed, but he was in such a hurry

341
00:24:28,640 --> 00:24:34,720
to be gone, and his spirit so greatly discomposed, that I had difficulty in finding out even

342
00:24:34,760 --> 00:24:38,600
so much as this.

343
00:24:38,600 --> 00:24:44,080
End of Chapter 47

344
00:24:44,080 --> 00:24:46,360
Chapter 48

345
00:24:46,360 --> 00:24:51,240
The whole party were in hopes of a letter from Mr. Bennett the next morning, but the post

346
00:24:51,240 --> 00:24:54,680
came in without bringing a single line from him.

347
00:24:54,680 --> 00:24:57,880
His family knew him to be on all communications.

348
00:24:58,040 --> 00:25:05,120
a most negligent and dilatory correspondent, but at such a time they had hoped for exertion.

349
00:25:05,120 --> 00:25:09,720
They were forced to conclude that he had no pleasing intelligence to send, but even of

350
00:25:09,720 --> 00:25:14,880
that they would have been glad to be certain. Mr. Gardiner had only waited for the letters

351
00:25:14,880 --> 00:25:20,440
before he set off. When he was gone they were certain at least of receiving constant

352
00:25:20,440 --> 00:25:26,640
information of what was going on, and their uncle promised, at parting, to prevail on

353
00:25:26,640 --> 00:25:30,880
Mr. Bennet to return to Longbourn as soon as he could, to the great

354
00:25:30,880 --> 00:25:35,240
consolation of his sister, who considered it as the only security for her

355
00:25:35,240 --> 00:25:40,600
husbands not being killed in a duel. Mrs. Gardiner and the children were to

356
00:25:40,600 --> 00:25:44,600
remain in Hartfordshire a few days longer, as the former thought her

357
00:25:44,600 --> 00:25:48,720
presence might be serviceable to her nieces. She shared in their

358
00:25:48,720 --> 00:25:52,400
attendance on Mrs. Bennet, and was of great comfort to them in their

359
00:25:52,400 --> 00:25:57,680
hours of freedom. Their other aunt, who visited them frequently and always,

360
00:25:57,680 --> 00:26:02,400
as she said, with the design of cheering and heartening them up, though as

361
00:26:02,400 --> 00:26:06,840
she never came without reporting some fresh instant of Wickham's extravagance

362
00:26:06,840 --> 00:26:10,840
or irregularity, she seldom went away without leaving them more

363
00:26:10,840 --> 00:26:16,480
dispirited than she found them. All Mariton seemed striving to blacken

364
00:26:16,480 --> 00:26:22,360
the man who, but three months before, had been almost an angel of light.

365
00:26:22,360 --> 00:26:26,280
She was declared to be in debt to every tradesman in the place, and

366
00:26:26,280 --> 00:26:30,440
his intrigues, all honoured with the title of seduction, had been

367
00:26:30,440 --> 00:26:35,360
extended into every tradesman's family. Everybody declared that he was

368
00:26:35,360 --> 00:26:39,760
the wickedest young man in the world, and everybody began to find out

369
00:26:39,760 --> 00:26:43,920
that they had always distrusted the appearance of his goodness.

370
00:26:43,920 --> 00:26:48,000
Elizabeth, though she did not credit above half of what was said,

371
00:26:48,000 --> 00:26:52,080
believed enough to make her former assurance of her sister's ruin more

372
00:26:52,120 --> 00:26:56,800
certain, and even Jane, who believed still less of it, became almost

373
00:26:56,800 --> 00:27:01,600
hopeless, more especially as the time was now come when, if they had

374
00:27:01,600 --> 00:27:06,440
gone to Scotland, which she had never before entirely disbared of,

375
00:27:06,440 --> 00:27:11,400
they must in all probability have gained some news of them.

376
00:27:11,400 --> 00:27:15,400
Mr. Gardiner left long-born on Sunday. On Tuesday his wife

377
00:27:15,400 --> 00:27:19,560
received a letter from him. They told them that, on his arrival,

378
00:27:19,560 --> 00:27:22,960
he had immediately found out his brother and persuaded him to come

379
00:27:22,960 --> 00:27:27,240
to Grace Church Street, that Mr. Bennett had been to Epsom and Clapham

380
00:27:27,240 --> 00:27:32,360
before his arrival, but without gaining any satisfactory information,

381
00:27:32,360 --> 00:27:35,320
and that he was now determined to inquire at all the principal

382
00:27:35,320 --> 00:27:39,240
hotels in town, as Mr. Bennett thought it possible they might have

383
00:27:39,240 --> 00:27:43,160
gone to one of them on their first coming to London before they

384
00:27:43,160 --> 00:27:47,720
procured lodgings. Mr. Gardiner himself did not expect any

385
00:27:47,760 --> 00:27:52,040
success from this measure, but as his brother was eager in it, he

386
00:27:52,040 --> 00:27:56,320
meant to assist him in pursuing it. He added that Mr. Bennett

387
00:27:56,320 --> 00:27:59,880
seemed wholly disinclined at present to leave London, and

388
00:27:59,880 --> 00:28:04,520
promised to write again very soon. There was also a post-script

389
00:28:04,520 --> 00:28:06,360
to this effect.

390
00:28:06,360 --> 00:28:10,000
I have written to Colonel Forster to desire him to find out,

391
00:28:10,000 --> 00:28:13,240
if possible, from some of the young man's intimates in the

392
00:28:13,240 --> 00:28:17,280
regiment, whether Wickham has any relations or connections who

393
00:28:17,320 --> 00:28:20,040
would be likely to know in what part of town he has now

394
00:28:20,040 --> 00:28:24,240
concealed himself. If there were any one that one could apply to

395
00:28:24,240 --> 00:28:28,480
with a probability of gaining such a clue as that, it might be

396
00:28:28,480 --> 00:28:33,440
of essential consequence. At present we have nothing to guide us.

397
00:28:33,440 --> 00:28:36,640
Colonel Forster will, I dare say, do everything in his power

398
00:28:36,640 --> 00:28:41,080
to satisfy us on this head. But, on second thoughts, perhaps

399
00:28:41,080 --> 00:28:44,240
Lizzie could tell us what relations he has now living, better

400
00:28:44,280 --> 00:28:46,880
than any other person.

401
00:28:46,880 --> 00:28:50,120
Elizabeth was at no loss to understand from where this

402
00:28:50,120 --> 00:28:54,320
deference to her authority proceeded, but it was not in her power

403
00:28:54,320 --> 00:28:57,840
to give any information of so satisfactory a nature as the

404
00:28:57,840 --> 00:29:01,480
compliment deserved. She had never heard of his having had any

405
00:29:01,480 --> 00:29:05,280
relations except a father and mother, both of whom had been

406
00:29:05,280 --> 00:29:09,280
dead many years. It was possible, however, that some of his

407
00:29:09,280 --> 00:29:12,800
companions in the blank sheer might be able to give more

408
00:29:12,840 --> 00:29:16,040
information, and though she was not very sanguine in

409
00:29:16,040 --> 00:29:20,160
expecting it, the application was a something to look forward

410
00:29:20,160 --> 00:29:25,120
to. Every day at Longbourn was now a day of anxiety, but the

411
00:29:25,120 --> 00:29:29,520
most anxious part of each was when the post was expected. The

412
00:29:29,520 --> 00:29:32,640
arrival of letters was a grand object of every morning's

413
00:29:32,640 --> 00:29:36,880
impatience. Through letters whatever of good or bad was to

414
00:29:36,880 --> 00:29:40,880
be told would be communicated, and every succeeding day was

415
00:29:40,960 --> 00:29:44,960
expected to bring some news of importance. But before they heard

416
00:29:44,960 --> 00:29:48,960
again from Mr. Gardiner, a letter arrived for their father from a

417
00:29:48,960 --> 00:29:53,440
different quarter from Mr. Collins, which, as Jane had

418
00:29:53,440 --> 00:29:56,240
received directions to open all that came for him in his

419
00:29:56,240 --> 00:30:00,240
absence, she accordingly read,

420
00:29:58,850 --> 00:30:06,570
Elizabeth, who knew what curiosities his letters always were, looked over her and read it likewise.

421
00:30:06,570 --> 00:30:08,130
It was as follows.

422
00:30:08,130 --> 00:30:16,610
My dear sir, I feel myself called upon by our relationship and my situation in life to condole

423
00:30:16,610 --> 00:30:22,170
with you on the grievous affliction you are now suffering under, of which we were yesterday

424
00:30:22,170 --> 00:30:25,850
informed by a letter from Hartfordshire.

425
00:30:25,850 --> 00:30:32,570
Be assured, my dear sir, that Mrs. Collins and myself sincerely sympathise with you and

426
00:30:32,570 --> 00:30:39,530
all your respectable family in your present distress, which must be of the bitterest kind,

427
00:30:39,530 --> 00:30:44,610
because proceeding from a cause which no time can remove.

428
00:30:44,610 --> 00:30:51,250
No arguments shall be wanting on my part that can alleviate so severe a misfortune, or

429
00:30:51,370 --> 00:30:56,930
that may comfort you under a circumstance that must be of all others the most afflicting

430
00:30:56,930 --> 00:30:59,410
to a parent's mind.

431
00:30:59,410 --> 00:31:04,450
The death of your daughter would have been a blessing in comparison to this, and it is

432
00:31:04,450 --> 00:31:10,210
the more to be lamented, because there is reason to suppose, as my dear Charlotte informs

433
00:31:10,210 --> 00:31:16,210
me, that this licentiousness of behaviour in your daughter has proceeded from a faulty

434
00:31:16,210 --> 00:31:18,530
degree of indulgence.

435
00:31:18,530 --> 00:31:24,650
Though, at the same time, for the consolation of yourself and Mrs. Bennet, I am inclined to

436
00:31:24,650 --> 00:31:30,810
think that her own disposition must be naturally bad, or she could not be guilty of such an

437
00:31:30,810 --> 00:31:34,450
enormity at so early an age.

438
00:31:34,450 --> 00:31:39,610
Howsoever that may be, you are grievously to be pitied, in which opinion I am not

439
00:31:39,610 --> 00:31:45,130
only joined by Mrs. Collins, but likewise by Lady Catherine and her daughter, to whom

440
00:31:45,170 --> 00:31:47,650
I have related the affair.

441
00:31:47,650 --> 00:31:52,290
They agree with me in apprehending that this false step in one daughter will be

442
00:31:52,290 --> 00:31:57,250
injurious to the fortunes of all the others, for who, as Lady Catherine

443
00:31:57,250 --> 00:32:02,970
herself condescendingly says, will connect themselves with such a family.

444
00:32:02,970 --> 00:32:07,730
And this consideration leads me moreover to reflect, with augmented

445
00:32:07,730 --> 00:32:12,690
satisfaction, on a certain event of last November, for had it been

446
00:32:12,730 --> 00:32:18,050
otherwise I must have been involved in all your sorrow and disgrace.

447
00:32:18,050 --> 00:32:22,850
Let me then advise you, dear sir, to console yourself as much as possible, to

448
00:32:22,850 --> 00:32:27,290
throw off your unworthy child from your affection for ever, and leave her to

449
00:32:27,290 --> 00:32:31,690
reap the fruits of her own heinous offence.

450
00:32:31,690 --> 00:32:36,910
I am, dear sir, et cetera, et cetera.

451
00:32:36,910 --> 00:32:40,150
Mr. Gardiner did not write again till he had received an answer from

452
00:32:40,150 --> 00:32:45,190
Colonel Forster, and then he had nothing of a pleasant nature to send.

453
00:32:45,190 --> 00:32:48,110
It was not known that Wickham had a single relationship with whom he

454
00:32:48,110 --> 00:32:54,190
kept up any connection, and it was certain that he had no near one living.

455
00:32:54,190 --> 00:32:57,750
His former acquaintances had been numerous, but since he had been in the

456
00:32:57,750 --> 00:33:02,110
militia it did not appear that he was on terms of particular friendship

457
00:33:02,110 --> 00:33:04,190
with any of them.

458
00:33:04,190 --> 00:33:07,590
There was no one, therefore, who could be pointed out as likely to give

459
00:33:07,590 --> 00:33:12,710
any news of him, and in the wretched state of his own finances there was a

460
00:33:12,710 --> 00:33:17,190
very powerful motive for secrecy, in addition to his fear of discovery

461
00:33:17,190 --> 00:33:22,150
by Lydia's relations, for it had just transpired that he had left gaming

462
00:33:22,150 --> 00:33:26,430
debts behind him to a very considerable amount.

463
00:33:26,430 --> 00:33:29,310
Colonel Forster believed that more than a thousand pounds would be

464
00:33:29,310 --> 00:33:33,110
necessary to clear his expenses at Brighton.

465
00:33:33,110 --> 00:33:37,230
He owed a good deal in town, but his debts of honor were still more

466
00:33:37,230 --> 00:33:39,110
formidable.

467
00:33:39,110 --> 00:33:42,430
Mr. Gardiner did not attempt to conceal these particulars from the

468
00:33:42,430 --> 00:33:44,730
long-born family.

469
00:33:44,730 --> 00:33:46,230
Jane heard them with horror.

470
00:33:46,230 --> 00:33:48,990
A game-ster, she cried.

471
00:33:48,990 --> 00:33:50,990
This is wholly unexpected.

472
00:33:50,990 --> 00:33:53,870
I had not an idea of it.

473
00:33:53,870 --> 00:33:57,190
Mr. Gardiner added in his letter that they might expect to see their

474
00:33:57,190 --> 00:34:01,510
father at home on the following day, which was Saturday.

475
00:34:01,510 --> 00:34:05,350
Rendered spiritless by the ill success of all their endeavors, he

476
00:34:05,350 --> 00:34:08,950
had yielded to his brother-in-law's entreaty that he would return to his

477
00:34:08,950 --> 00:34:12,830
family, and leave it to him to do whatever occasion might suggest to

478
00:34:12,830 --> 00:34:16,470
be advisable for continuing their pursuit.

479
00:34:16,470 --> 00:34:19,270
When Mrs. Bennett was told of this, she did not express so much

480
00:34:19,270 --> 00:34:23,470
satisfaction as her children expected, considering what her anxiety

481
00:34:23,470 --> 00:34:25,630
for his life had been before.

482
00:34:25,630 --> 00:34:29,230
What, is he coming home and without poor Lydia?

483
00:34:29,230 --> 00:34:30,230
She cried.

484
00:34:30,230 --> 00:34:33,670
Sure he will not leave London before he has found them.

485
00:34:33,670 --> 00:34:38,070
Who is to fight Wickham and make him marry her if he comes away?

486
00:34:38,070 --> 00:34:41,870
As Mrs. Gardiner began to wish to be at home, it was settled that

487
00:34:41,870 --> 00:34:45,310
she and the children should go to London at the same time that

488
00:34:45,310 --> 00:34:47,630
Mr. Bennett came from it.

489
00:34:47,630 --> 00:34:50,510
The coach, therefore, took them the first stage of their journey

490
00:34:50,510 --> 00:34:53,910
and brought its master back to Longbourn.

491
00:34:53,910 --> 00:34:57,630
Mrs. Gardiner went away, and all the perplexity about Elizabeth

492
00:34:57,630 --> 00:34:59,070
and her Darbyshire friend.

493
00:34:59,230 --> 00:35:04,170
that had attended her from that part of the world. His name had never been voluntarily

494
00:35:04,170 --> 00:35:09,770
mentioned before them by her niece, and the kind of half-expectation which Mrs. Gardner

495
00:35:09,770 --> 00:35:16,210
had formed of there being followed by a letter from him had ended in nothing. Elizabeth had

496
00:35:16,210 --> 00:35:21,010
received none since her return that could come from Pemberley.

497
00:35:21,010 --> 00:35:25,730
The present unhappy state of the family rendered any other excuse for the lowness of her

498
00:35:25,730 --> 00:35:31,490
spirits unnecessary. Nothing, therefore, could be fairly conjectured from that.

499
00:35:31,490 --> 00:35:35,570
Though Elizabeth, who was by this time tolerably well acquainted with her own

500
00:35:35,570 --> 00:35:41,090
feelings, was perfectly aware that, had she known nothing of Darcy, she could

501
00:35:41,090 --> 00:35:45,930
have borne the dread of Lydia's infamy somewhat better. It would have spared

502
00:35:45,930 --> 00:35:50,610
her, she thought, one sleepless night out of two.

503
00:35:50,610 --> 00:35:53,710
When Mr. Bennet arrived he had all the appearance of his usual

504
00:35:53,710 --> 00:35:58,330
philosophic composure. He said as little as he had ever been in the habit of

505
00:35:58,330 --> 00:36:02,950
saying, made no mention of the business that had taken him away, and it was

506
00:36:02,950 --> 00:36:07,550
some time before his daughters had courage to speak of it. It was not

507
00:36:07,550 --> 00:36:11,710
till the afternoon, when he had joined them at tea, that Elizabeth ventured

508
00:36:11,710 --> 00:36:16,590
to introduce the subject, and then, on her briefly expressing her sorrow for

509
00:36:16,590 --> 00:36:21,590
what he must have endured, he replied, Say nothing of that, who should

510
00:36:21,590 --> 00:36:27,230
suffer but myself. It has been my own doing, and I ought to feel it.

511
00:36:27,230 --> 00:36:32,230
You must not be too severe upon yourself, replied Elizabeth. You may well

512
00:36:32,230 --> 00:36:37,510
warn me against such an evil. Human nature is so prone to fall into it.

513
00:36:37,510 --> 00:36:41,430
No, Lizzie, let me once in my life feel how much I have been to

514
00:36:41,430 --> 00:36:45,830
blame. I am not afraid of being overpowered by the impression. It

515
00:36:45,830 --> 00:36:47,550
will pass away soon enough.

516
00:36:47,550 --> 00:36:52,710
Do you suppose them to be in London? Yes, where else can they be so

517
00:36:52,710 --> 00:36:58,790
well concealed? And Lydia used to want to go to London, added Kitty.

518
00:36:58,790 --> 00:37:02,710
She is happy, then, said her father, dryly, and her residence there

519
00:37:02,710 --> 00:37:08,090
will probably be of some duration. Then, after short silence, he

520
00:37:08,090 --> 00:37:12,270
continued, Lizzie, I bear you no ill will for being justified in

521
00:37:12,270 --> 00:37:16,270
your advice to me last May, which considering the event shows

522
00:37:16,470 --> 00:37:20,870
some greatness of mind. They were interrupted by Miss Bennet, who

523
00:37:20,870 --> 00:37:25,670
came to fetch her mother's tea. This is a parade, he cried, which

524
00:37:25,670 --> 00:37:30,270
does one good. It gives such an elegance to misfortune. Another

525
00:37:30,270 --> 00:37:34,070
day I will do the same. I will sit to my library in my nightcap

526
00:37:34,070 --> 00:37:37,350
and powdering down and give as much trouble as I can. Or

527
00:37:37,350 --> 00:37:40,670
perhaps I may defer it till Kitty runs away.

528
00:37:40,670 --> 00:37:45,110
I am not going to run away, Papa, said Kitty fretfully, if

529
00:37:45,150 --> 00:37:49,470
I should ever go to Brighton I would behave better than Lydia.

530
00:37:49,470 --> 00:37:52,590
You go to Brighton. I would not trust you so near it is

531
00:37:52,590 --> 00:37:56,750
east-born for fifty pounds. No, Kitty, I have at least learnt

532
00:37:56,750 --> 00:38:01,070
to be cautious, and you will feel the effects of it. No officer

533
00:38:01,070 --> 00:38:03,990
is ever to enter into my house again, nor even to pass

534
00:38:03,990 --> 00:38:07,950
through the village. Balls will be absolutely prohibited unless

535
00:38:07,950 --> 00:38:11,070
you stand up with one of your sisters, and you are never to

536
00:38:11,070 --> 00:38:14,190
stir out of doors till you can prove that you have spent ten

537
00:38:14,230 --> 00:38:18,790
minutes of every day in a rational manner. Kitty, who took all

538
00:38:18,790 --> 00:38:22,590
these threats in a serious light, began to cry.

539
00:38:22,590 --> 00:38:27,990
Well, well, said he, do not make yourself unhappy. If you are a

540
00:38:27,990 --> 00:38:31,670
good girl for the next ten years I will take you to a review at

541
00:38:31,670 --> 00:38:36,650
the end of them.
